            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Lin Wong is a human bridge, a life-long resident of the city that shaped her. Born in the Richmond District to a seamstress mother from Hong Kong and a second-generation Irish-American Muni driver, her childhood was a vibrant blend of Cantonese traditions and working-class San Francisco grit. She grew up navigating two worlds, translating for her mother at appointments and inheriting her father's deep-seated belief in community solidarity.\n\nThis foundation led her to SF State to study Social Work, where she felt an immediate calling. However, her formal education was cut short in her third year when her mother was diagnosed with a chronic illness. Mei-Lin left school without a second thought, becoming her mother\u2019s primary caregiver and advocate. For five years, she navigated the labyrinthine healthcare system, fighting for culturally competent care and translating complex medical jargon. This experience, more than any degree, became her true diploma.\n\nAfter her mother\u2019s passing, returning to academia felt hollow. Instead, she found her purpose as a Community Health Worker in a Chinatown clinic, a role she has now held for over twenty years. Her life is contained within a one-mile radius, her 0.8-mile walk to work a daily pilgrimage through the neighborhood she serves. She lives in a modest, rent-controlled apartment filled with photos and her mother\u2019s jade plants.\n\nMei-Lin is single, a past long-term relationship having buckled under the strain of her caregiving. But she is far from lonely; her family is the elderly man she ensures has his prescriptions, the young immigrant mother she connects with nutritional programs, and her tight-knit group of colleagues. Her dream isn\u2019t of retirement or travel, but of securing funding for an intergenerational health program, connecting youth with seniors. For Mei-Lin, success isn\u2019t measured by her income, but by the strength and well-being of the community she has woven herself into, thread by loving thread."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the rumble of her father's 38 Geary bus, holding her mother\u2019s hand as they rode his route. Her father would catch her eye in the giant rearview mirror and wink, a silent acknowledgment of his two worlds colliding. Her mother, smelling of starch and tea, would whisper questions in Cantonese about the passing streets. At ten years old, translating between the Irish brogue of the driver\u2019s seat and the quiet Cantonese of the passenger, Mei-Lin felt like the essential, vibrating pin holding her family\u2019s universe together.\n\n2.\nThe hospital room felt cold, the air thin. The doctor\u2019s words were a clinical drone, but Mei-Lin only saw her mother\u2019s face\u2014the tightening around her eyes, the confusion. In that moment, her social work textbooks, her degree, her own future, all evaporated. A fierce, protective clarity washed over her. There was no decision to be made, only a path to be taken. Walking out of SF State for the last time didn't feel like a sacrifice; it felt like stepping into her true, non-negotiable purpose.\n\n3.\nA few years into her mother\u2019s illness, she remembers an afternoon spent repotting jade plants. Her mother\u2019s hands, frail but knowing, guided hers in the soil. \u201cToo much water, they rot. Too little, they wither,\u201d she\u2019d said softly in Cantonese. It wasn\u2019t about the plants. Mei-Lin understood she was being taught the delicate balance of care\u2014how to tend to a life with gentle consistency, not smothering concern. She inherited a living legacy that day, one that required patience and attentive love to keep alive.\n\n4.\nHer first week at the Chinatown clinic, an elderly man, Mr. Wei, sat clutching a new prescription, his shoulders slumped in fear. Mei-Lin recognized the look instantly\u2014it was her mother\u2019s. She sat down, switched to Cantonese, and slowly explained each pill. As the fear in his eyes was replaced by understanding, the grief she still carried for her mother alchemized into purpose. This was her classroom, these were her people. She didn't need a diploma; her expertise was etched into her heart.\n\n5.\nJust last spring, she saw it: the teenage son of a young mother she'd helped, now volunteering to walk Mr. Wei home with his groceries. She watched from her office window as the boy slowed his pace to match the elder\u2019s, listening intently to a story. They were a bridge she hadn't intentionally built, a connection forged from the community she'd nurtured. It was a quiet, profound validation\u2014a glimpse of her dream, alive and breathing on the Grant Avenue sidewalk."
